%I A397558 #9 Jul 01 2026 01:08:03
%S A397558 4,10,4,50,4,26,4,10196,4
%N A397558 Number of Hadamard-diagonalizable graphs of order 4*n.
%C A397558 A (simple, undirected) graph G is called Hadamard-diagonalizable if there exists a Hadamard matrix H for which H^T*A*H is diagonal, where A is the adjacency matrix of G (A can equivalently be chosen to be the Laplacian matrix of G).
%C A397558 a(n) = 4 whenever n is odd and there exists a Hadamard matrix of order 4*n.
%C A397558 There is also one Hadamard-diagonalizable graph of order 1 (K_1) and two Hadamard-diagonalizable graphs of order 2 (K_2 and 2K_1).
%C A397558 Hadamard-diagonalizable graphs are necessarily regular (A005176) and integral (A077027).
%H A397558 J. Breen, S. Butler, M. Fuentes, B. Lidický, M. Phillips, A. W. N. Riasanovksy, S.-Y. Song, R. R. Villagrán, C. Wiseman, and X. Zhang, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2007.09235">Hadamard diagonalizable graphs of order at most 36</a>, The Electronic Journal of Combinatorics, 29, #P2.16 (2022). arXiv:2007.09235 [math.CO], 2020.
%e A397558 a(3) = 4 since there are 4 different 4*3 = 12-vertex Hadamard-diagonalizable graphs: K_{12}, K_{6,6}, 12K_1, and 2K_6.
%Y A397558 Cf. A005176, A007299, A077027.
%K A397558 nonn,hard,more
%O A397558 1,1
%A A397558 _Nathaniel Johnston_, Jun 30 2026
